From 41d42f9e3359e45ad7155056f14d1f7ceed22d19 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: John Wiegley <johnw@newartisans.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 2026 16:48:37 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] fix(codex): gate subagent-thread rebinds and fork subagent
 bindings

Codex refuses user-initiated turns on any thread whose session_meta says
thread_source=subagent: `codex resume` loads such a thread and even
auto-continues goal-mode work, but the first typed message makes the TUI
exit status 1 with "Error: turn/start failed in TUI", killing the tmux
session in an error loop.

Sessions end up bound to subagent threads via three id-rotation paths:

- The notify hook: a completing subagent fires the same
  agent-turn-complete event as the main thread, and
  bindCodexSessionFromHook accepted any payload id with no quality gate
  (unlike the Claude clear-rebind heuristics).
- The live-process FD probe: a codex TUI holds the rollouts of the
  subagents it spawned open alongside the main thread, so the probe can
  surface a subagent id.
- The cold-start disk scan: the most-recent rollout for a project may be
  a subagent's.

And once bound, an adopted subagent thread also arises when an earlier
mid-flight restart resumed one directly.

Three defenses, all reading the rollout's session_meta head:

- Rebind gate (shouldRejectCodexSubagentRebind): reject subagent-sourced
  candidates on all three rotation paths. The hook path logs a lifecycle
  reject event; the disk scan filters them out of candidacy in the walk
  so it still selects the best user-sourced match; candidates with no
  flushed rollout bind (fail-open).
- Restart safety net: buildCodexCommand launches subagent-sourced
  bindings with `codex fork <sid>` instead of `codex resume <sid>`. The
  fork carries full context into a fresh thread_source=user thread that
  accepts input; the probe rebinds to the fork's new id once it is up.

The gate stops poisoning at the source; the fork net is the backstop for
bindings poisoned before the gate existed.
